article.headline: Phoenix manages eighth win of the season
article.linkText: DeForge leads Mercury past San Antonio
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Before the season began, Anna DeForge was looking
for a job.

Now, she is the player that the Phoenix Mercury hope to build
around after its less-than-successful season.

DeForge scored 19 of her career-high 24 points in the first half
and helped give Phoenix an 89-62 win over San Antonio Friday night.

All with a broken nose.

DeForge, who had not played in the league the last two seasons,
hit her first six shots and was 7-of-8 in the first half --
including 4-of-5 from 3-point range -- as Phoenix took a 48-34
halftime lead.

The Mercury's lowest point total this season was 46.

"At the beginning of the season I was just happy to be on a
WNBA team and having a job in this league," said DeForge, who
injured her nose during Wednesday's loss to Minnesota.

"What a great way to end what was a tough season."

DeForge said she didn't want to play with a mask to protect her
nose because it blocked her vision.

She finished 9-of-13 from the field -- all her 3-point attempts
were in the first half -- and has averaged 19.4 points in her last
five games.

"Games like this just work out," she said. "I was just in one
of those shooters zones and the rhythm, everything felt good. I was
getting great looks."

Phoenix (8-25) surpassed its season high for points -- 77 on July
15 in overtime against Los Angeles -- with 5:25 left in the game.

It was the largest margin of victory this season -- well better
than a 15-point over Houston June 14.

Margo Dydek scored a season-high 22 points for San Antonio
(12-21).

"We just go back to where we went wrong and we just start to
correct it because that's what we've done since we took over,"
said San Antonio coach Shell Daley, who replaced Candi Harvey on
July 26.

Kayte Christensen added a career-best 16 points and Lisa
Harrison had 11 for the Mercury, who remain 1{ games behind
Washington for the worst record in the WNBA.

Sylvia Crawley added 12 points and eight rebounds for San
Antonio, which had beaten Phoenix twice in their first three
meetings.

"We just needed some defensive stops and we didn't get that,"
said Crawley. "We let outside factors rattle us."

The Mercury took advantage of 22 Silver Star turnovers, scoring
30 points off those mistakes.

"Well, I guess we saved our best for last," said Mercury coach
John Shumate. "How sweet it was."

The Silver Stars, who reached the Western Conference finals as
the Utah Starzz last season, had come in winners of three of four,
all against playoff-contending teams.

Neither team will be in the postseason and both end their
seasons Saturday.

The Silver Stars are at Los Angeles, while Phoenix visits
Sacramento.
